[2
Date: Fri, 11 Sep 1998 15:49:34 CAT
From: Anna Mouton <anna@moon.ovi.ac.za>

Mycobacteriosis in fish is generally caused by _Mycobacterium_ species that
occur in the environment. Aquarists have been known to develop a
granulomatous skin infection from continuous exposure to infected tanks,
but this is uncommon. As an example, I have had a tank of goldfish
infected with _Mycobacterium chelonei_ for over five years and do not take
special precautions when working with the tank, but have not suffered an
infection (yet). Persons who are immunosuppressed should obviously avoid
direct contact with aquaria. Open wounds are likely to increase the risk
of infection, both with _Mycobacterium_ spp and other bacteria. There have
been several reports of fatal wound infections with marine bacteria (a
reference to one is given below). However, the risk to the average person
with normal immune function from touching an aquarium exhibit is likely to
be far less than from eating a seafood platter.
Reference: Fraser et al. 1997. Rapidly fatal infection due to
_Photobacterium (Vibrio) damsela_. Clinical Infectious Diseases, October
1997, 25, p935-936.
--
Dr A. Mouton
Diagnostic Bacteriologist
Onderstepoort Veterinary Institute
Agricultural Research Council
South Africa.
e-mail: anna@moon.ovi.ac.za
