[3
Date: Fri, 11 Sep 1998 18:40:51 -0700
From: Stephen A. Berger, M.D. <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>

I suspect that controlled human trials of handling contaminated marine life
have not been done; however, a number of potentially pathogenic
non-tuberculous mycobacteria have been found in water and marine life.
Three that come to mind are _Mycobacterium xenopi_ ("frog"), _M. chelonae_
("turtle") and _M. marinum_. The latter causes skin and soft tissue
infection following traumatic inoculation from aquaria and swimming pools
(swimming pool granuloma).
--
Dr. Steve Berger
e-mail: mberger@post.tau.ac.il
