[5
Date: Mon, 14 Sep 1998 13:48:06 EDT
From: J.L. Dunn VMD <DUNNL@aol.com>

We have surveyed the sediments of a number of exhibits at a public aquarium
and found that we recovered Mycobacterium sp. in >40% of the samples. The
positive samples occurred in both fresh and salt water exhibits as well as
in ambient, heated and refrigerated exhibits. Marine mammal filtration
system sediments were consistently negative.
I think the presence of these organisms represents more of a risk to
aquarium personnel, who may have considerable contact with sediments, than
to members of the general public who presumably are simply getting their
hands wet. The risk to immunocompromised individuals of either group would
likely be greater. Many millions of individuals have handled animals from
interactive aquatic exhibits without any observed ill effects though the
lengthy incubation period of many mycobacterial species might make it
difficult to demonstrate a simple exposure/infection effect.
I am unaware of whether similar surveys of natural beaches, tide pools,
etc. have been conducted. It may well be that these are more ubiquitous
organisms than we have previously considered them to be.
--
J.L. Dunn, VMD
e-mail: DUNNL@aol.com
